If anything seems off to you, please feel free to write me at vlogize [AT] gmail [DOT] com. --- Can I Compile gRPC to the Web with Emscripten? Here's What You Need to Know! Compiling libraries like gRPC to work within the web environment can be a daunting task, especially if you're encountering errors during the build process. If you're struggling to get gRPC compiled on the web using Emscriptenwithout using gRPC-Webyou're not alone! Lets dive into the common problems and their solutions, as well as what you need to keep in mind when taking on this challenging project. Understanding the Challenge When you're trying to compile a library like gRPC to WebAssembly (WASM) using Emscripten, it's crucial to be aware that you're essentially porting the library to a new platform. This effort can be compared to porting applications to Windows or macOS, as it requires in-depth changes and adjustments. Key Errors Encountered While working through this compilation process, you might face several common errors, including but not limited to: Unsupported Clang Arguments: clang+ + : error: unsupported argument '-g' to option '-Wa,' Platform Detection Issues: error: "Could not auto-detect platform" Type Name Errors: grpc error: unknown type name 'gpr_atm' Missing Files: emcc: error: libz.a: No such file or directory Feature Restrictions: wasm-ld: error: --shared-memory is disallowed by ex_data.c.o because it was not compiled with 'atomics' or 'bulk-memory' features. Missing Header Files: fatal error: 'sys/eventfd.h' file not found and fatal error: 'sys/epoll.h' file not found These errors signal that there are fundamental differences between how gRPC operates in traditional environments versus how it needs to function on the web. The Path to Resolution 1. Modifying Makefiles and Compiler Options The first step is to adapt the Makefiles to account for the web environment. Youll have to dive into the specific compiler options and adjust them to eliminate any unsupported arguments. Familiarizing yourself with the flags and configurations used within Emscripten is essential in this step. 2. Handling Dependencies Like libz libz (the zlib compression library) has been additionally ported for use with Emscripten, and you need to ensure that you compile and integrate it correctly into your project. This means not just fetching the library but also compiling it according to the specifications required by WASM. 3. Reimplementing Unsupported Features Since features like epoll and eventfd dont have direct equivalents in the web world, it may become necessary to create alternative implementations for these parts of the code. Understanding the underlying functionalities of these components will aid in designing their web-friendly counterparts. 4. Configuring Shared Memory Properly To use shared memory, you should compile with the flag -pthread, and ensure your web server has the Cross-Origin-Opener-Policy (COOP) and Cross-Origin-Embedder-Policy (COEP) enabled. This preparation is critical for utilizing SharedArrayBuffer, which is essential for enabling shared memory features in your application. Conclusion Embarking on the journey to compile gRPC to the web with Emscripten is by no means trivial. It requires an understanding of both gRPCs architecture and the specific constraints and affordances of the web platform. It's an undertaking that demands patience, learning, and adaptability, but the reward of having gRPC work seamlessly in a web environment is worth the effort. By recognizing the challenges and applying the outlined solutions, you'll be better equipped to tackle this complex but fulfilling task. Happy coding!
